  "theory": "A BJT (Bipolar Junction Transistor) acts as a switch by operating in two regions: Saturation (ON) and Cut-off (OFF). In the Common Emitter configuration, when the base input voltage Vin is HIGH (logic 1), sufficient base current IB flows through RB, causing the transistor to saturate — collector current IC flows and output Vout ≈ 0V (like a closed switch). When Vin is LOW (logic 0), no base current flows, transistor enters cut-off — IC = 0 and Vout = VCC (open switch). BJTs are widely used in digital logic circuits, relay drivers, and motor control.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "Saturation region: VBE ≈ 0.7V (Si), VCE(sat) ≈ 0.2V → switch is ON",
    "Cut-off region: IB = 0, IC ≈ 0, VCE ≈ VCC → switch is OFF",
    "Base resistor RB limits base current: IB = (Vin − VBE) / RB",
    "For saturation: IB must exceed IC(sat) / β (β = hFE = current gain)",
    "NPN: current flows from Collector to Emitter when switched ON"
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Relay and solenoid drivers in industrial control",
    "LED and lamp switching circuits",
    "Digital-to-analog interface in microcontroller outputs"
  ]
